issue.title: Vuetify: card view for object browser
issue.body:
By default, we should display the existing list view, but provide the user to select "card view", like how "all projects dashboard" works.

In card view, the user will be able to see image previews on the cards. When a card is clicked, it will be opened in gallery view.

### AC:
* optional card view is accessible in object browser for vuetify app
  * image previews show up in cards 
  * by default, list view should be enabled
  * users should be notified or have some banner that indicates that using card view will generate additional egress (talk to design team about expected experience)
* demo this experience to (or share screenshots with) design team before merging

issue.title: Create Testplan for Object Versioning
issue.body:
Slack channel "object-versioning"
Design documents can be found here: https://github.com/storj/qa-storj/issues/517

First Brainstorming:
Customer and storage node payments for a bucket with multiple versions of the same file
Server side copy and server side move across buckets with different version settings
1. To a bucket that has versioning enabled. Should add one version to it.
2. To a bucket that has version disabled. Should override existing version.

Create 3 versions of the same file and delete the middle one.
Create new bucket should inherrit version from project level. Same goes for creating a project inherrits from user level.
Admin UI should behave the same.
Suspend versioning on a bucket that had versioning enabled. 3 versions of a file exists. Try to upload the same file again. -> the newsest file gets overriden. The older 2 versions stay intact.
Can a project member with an restriced access grant modify the version flag on a bucket? Which permissions does the access grant need?
Does updating file metadata create a new version?
List old versions in order
Restore old version


Bonus:
Can a customer set a maximum number of versions?
Can a customer pin specific versions to make sure they can't be deleted by maleware?

We should update this command and remove apply-free-coupons.

issue.title: Carryover invoice charges cannot be paid via storjscan token payments
issue.body:
During the most recent invoice cycle, it was noticed that one invoice was unable to be paid via a users storjscan token balance. After further investigation, it was found that despite the fact that the user had more than enough tokens to cover the entire invoice amount, the invoice could not be paid because there was a charge from a previous invoice on the users newly created invoice.

**How does a previous invoice charge end up on a new invoice?**
Stripe has something called a minimum charge amount. If the total balance due on any given invoice is less than this minimum amount (50 cents for USD), then stripe will mark the invoice as paid, and carry the charges forward into the users next invoice.

**Why can't a token balance pay an invoice with a previous charge?**
To allow a user to pay for an invoice with storj tokens, we use a credit note on the invoice to reduce the users balance due on the invoice by the amount of tokens they have available to use. If they have more tokens available than the amount due on the invoice, the invoice is paid in full, and the users token balance is reduced by the invoice amount. However, credit notes can only be used to reduce charges that are generated by the invoice itself (I.E. any invoice items on the invoice). Previous charges are not charges that originate from the current invoice, therefore their charge amount cannot be reduced by a credit note on the current invoice. The credit note would need to be applied on the invoice where the charges came from, which would be the previous invoice.

issue.title: Add the ability to update invoice status with a new command

labels.name: Injection
labels.description: Added to sprint after sprint planning

issue.body:
## Description
We need the ability to bulk-update invoice statues from past invoices that are essentially uncollectible. 

The name of the command should be updateInvoiceStatues? (or whatever the engineer who works on this thinks it should be)

## Acceptance Criteria
- The command must allow you to specify what you want the invoice status to be updated to for "OPEN" invoices.
    - paid, void, or uncollectible (https://stripe.com/docs/invoicing/overview#invoice-statuses)
- The command must allow you to input a date range (start and end date) to find invoices on Stripe to update the invoice status
- The command should NOT change the invoice status for any invoice that is draft, paid, void, or uncollectible

We want to release the new satellite admin web app progressively while running the current one until the new one is complete and it offers all the functionalities that the current one has without issues.

## What needs to be done?

Make the appropriate changes in the current satellite admin server to be able to implement the authorization and new endpoints.

## Acceptance criteria

- Current satellite admin server is refactored to accept the authorization and endpoint implementation of the new satellite admin API.

issue.title: Revert pending_objects table changes (code/configurations)

milestone.title: Object Versioning Pre-Requisite Work
milestone.description:
While creating the blueprint and doing the POC for object versioning, we discovered we needed some prerequisite work to make the implementation possible.

Main portion of object versioning implementation will be build on the top of `objects` table. Currently objects doesn't fit well into object versioning design. We need to refactor DB schema to make future changes less complex and less prone to issues. Objects table needs to be split into two tables, pending and committed object, as now we are keeping all in a single table. By doing this we will simplify table (which will keep only committed objects) and will remove some parts that are incompatible with S3 design (e.g. version column) which we would like to follow for good compatibility.

Second reason why we would like to go into this direction is performance impact we predict we will have from separating tables. Currently objects are differentiated into pending and committed by `status` column which is not indexed or part of primary key. Adding secondary index this such large table might be problematic and we would like to avoid it. When `objects` table will keep only committed objects we should have faster "read" path for committed objects because we won't need to use `status` column.

One potential problem we can have with this approach is that while uploading an object will will require transactions across tables to do commit which can have negative performance impact.  We need to assess this impact while doing this refactoring as soon as possible.

Whole implementation will be done in steps and most of time will be behind feature flag.

Extra context from Arch Review https://storjlabs.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ENG/pages/2579824641/2023-05-11+Arch+Review

Things to do before starting work on the implementation:
- Apply initial DB schema to split objects table
- Add new code to support it
- Migrate data
- Drop unused elements in DB schema
- Drop/adjust old code

We decided that for now we won't keep `pending_objects` table because of performance impact of processing two tables. We need to revert changes we did for this feature.

Acceptance Criteria:
* disable pending objects table feature flag on satellites
* remove pending_objects implementation (save it under `pending_objects` branch)
